 <insight_2_explanation>\n            }}\n        ]\n    }}\n\n# Grounding Rules\n\nPoints supported by data should list their data references as follows:\n\n\"This is an example sentence supported by multiple data references [Data: <dataset name> (record ids); <dataset name> (record ids)].\"\n\nDo not list more than 5 record ids in a single reference. Instead, list the top 5 most relevant record ids and add \"+more\" to indicate that there are more.\n\nFor example:\n\"The concept of Expected Value is fundamental to Chapter 8 and is illustrated through multiple examples [Data: Concepts (5, 7, 12); Examples (3, 8, 15, +more)].\"\n\nwhere 5, 7, 12, 3, 8, and 15 represent the id (not the index) of the relevant data record.\n\nDo not include information where the supporting evidence for it is not provided.\n\n# Example Input\n-----------\nText:\n\nEntities\n\nid,entity,description\n1,FOCUS GROUP,Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals.\n2,MARKET RESEARCH,Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively.\n3. SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS, Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used to calculate it.\nRelationships\n\nid,source,target,description\n10,FOCUS GROUP,MARKET RESEARCH,Focus group is related to market research. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n11,MARKET RESEARCH,FOCUS GROUP,Market research is related to focus group. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n\nOutput:\n{{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter 8: Risk and Uncertainty\",\n    \"summary\": \"Chapter 8 covers the following Learning Outcomes. C. Decision-Making Techniques 6. Dealing with risk and uncertainty in decision making a) Suggest research techniques to reduce uncertainty (e.g. focus groups, market research). b) Explain the use of simulation, expected values and sensitivity. c) Apply expected values and sensitivity to decision-making problems. d) Apply the techniques of maximax, maximin and minimax regret to decision-making problems, including the production of profit tables. e) Interpret a decision tree and use it to solve a multi-stage decision problem. f) Calculate the value of perfect and imperfect information. \",\n    \"rating\": 7.0,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact severity rating is high due to the fundamental importance of bookkeeping in accounting.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Focus groups and market research are important research techniques to reduce uncertainty\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Companies often use focus groups and/or market research to deal with uncertainty. Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals. Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively. [Data: Concepts (1, 2); Relationships (10, 11)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Explain and apply sensitivity analysis to decision-making problems\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used in making that decision. It looks at one variable at a time and measures how much the variable can change by (in percentage terms) before affecting the decision. The smaller the percentage, the more sensitive the decision is to that variable. Sensitivity % = Profit/Variable  [Data: Concepts (3)]\"\n        }}\n    ]\n}}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\n324,\"\"\"REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"Revenue\"\" is the total amount of income generated by the sale of goods or services related to a company's primary operations. It is a key indicator of a company's financial performance and is used to assess profitability and growth. Revenue is calculated as the product of sales units and sales price, representing the total income before any costs or expenses are deducted. Recently, revenue decreased by 8.3% from $72,025 to $66,028, but this figure was still 14.6% higher than expected given the market decline.\",13\n205,\"\"\"TARGET PROFIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Target profit\"\" is the projected profit that a company aims to achieve, calculated as a percentage of target revenue. It represents the desired profit from the sale of a product, determined by dividing the total required profit by the number of units to be sold.\",2\n1883,\"\"\"PERFORMANCE ASSESSMENT OF AT CO IN 20X9\"\"\",\"\"\"The performance assessment of AT Co in 20X9 involves evaluating various financial and non-financial metrics, including revenue, cost of sales, gross profit, indirect expenses, and net operating profit, as well as non-financial performance indicators such as student transfer rates, late enrolments, exam pass rates, labor turnover, and student complaints.\"\"\",6\n1059,\"\"\"GROSS PROFIT MARGIN\"\"\",\"The \"\"Gross Profit Margin\"\" is a financial metric calculated as Gross Profit divided by Revenue, multiplied by 100. It represents the percentage of revenue that exceeds the cost of goods sold, thereby indicating the profitability of a product or service. This metric is crucial for assessing the efficiency and effectiveness of a company's management in generating profit from sales. For instance, the gross profit margin increased from 27.7% to 36.3% in 20X9, reflecting positively on management's performance. Additionally, the gross profit margin for quarter 1 is 52%, and for quarter 2, it is 50%, further illustrating the company's profitability over different periods.\",5\n1881,\"\"\"NET OPERATING PROFIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Net operating profit\"\" is the profit earned from a firm's normal core business operations, excluding deductions of interest and tax. Recently, net operating profit fell from $3.635 million to $2.106 million. Despite this decline, the outcome was viewed positively considering the challenging market conditions.\",5\n370,\"\"\"GROSS PROFIT\"\"\",\"Gross profit is the difference between sales revenue and the cost of goods sold (COGS). It indicates the efficiency of production and the profitability of core business activities. Gross profit is the profit a company makes after deducting the costs associated with making and selling its products, or the costs associated with providing its services.\",4\n1603,\"\"\"SUNDAY TRADING\"\"\",\"\"\"Sunday trading refers to the practice of opening a retail store for business on Sundays, which can lead to increased revenue and additional costs.\"\"\",4\n1886,\"\"\"MARKETING COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Marketing costs are the expenses related to promoting and selling a new product. In 20X9, marketing costs increased by 42.1%, which was essential for attracting new students and improving service awareness.\"\"\",2\n1600,\"\"\"TARGET REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"Target revenue is the projected total income that a company aims to achieve from sales of a product.\"\"\",2\n1889,\"\"\"INTERACTIVE WEBSITE\"\"\",\"\"\"The interactive website was introduced to improve service quality and pass rates, contributing to higher student numbers and revenue.\"\"\",1\n1605,\"\"\"MANAGER'S BONUS\"\"\",\"\"\"Manager's bonus is an additional payment made to a manager based on the extra sales generated by Sunday trading.\"\"\",1\n1604,\"\"\"SUPPLIER DISCOUNT\"\"\",\"\"\"Supplier discount is a reduction in the purchase price offered by a supplier when certain conditions, such as a minimum annual spend, are met.\"\"\",1\n1890,\"\"\"STUDENT HELPLINE\"\"\",\"\"\"The student helpline was introduced to improve service quality and pass rates, contributing to higher student numbers and revenue.\"\"\",1\n1879,\"\"\"COST OF SALES\"\"\",\"Cost of sales, also known as cost of goods sold (COGS), represents the direct costs attributable to the production of the goods sold by a company. For the year 20X9, the expected cost of sales was $47.738 million, but the actual cost of sales was $42.056 million, showing a reduction of $5.682 million.\",5\n1880,\"\"\"INDIRECT EXPENSES\"\"\",\"\"\"Indirect expenses are costs that are not directly tied to the production of goods or services, such as marketing, property, staff training, and other operational costs.\"\"\",2\n2249,\"\"\"AVERAGE PRICE PER TIE\"\"\",\"\"\"The average price achieved for the ties sold, calculated as total sales revenue divided by the number of ties sold. For quarter 1, it is $15.20 per tie, and for quarter 2, it is $17.50 per tie.\"\"\",1\n1882,\"\"\"FREELANCE LECTURERS\"\"\",\"\"\"Freelance lecturers are non-employee instructors hired by the company to teach students when there are not enough of the company's own lecturers to meet tuition needs.\"\"\",1\n1884,\"\"\"FREELANCE LECTURER COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Freelance lecturer costs fell by $2.188m, contributing to the overall reduction in cost of sales.\"\"\",1\n1885,\"\"\"ONLINE MARKING SYSTEM\"\"\",\"\"\"The online marking system was expected to cut costs by $4m, but it likely saved $3.494m, contributing to the reduction in cost of sales.\"\"\",1\n1606,\"\"\"ENERGY COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Energy costs refer to the expenses incurred for energy consumption. In this context, it is calculated based on the total hours worked and the cost per hour. Additionally, energy costs encompass the expenses for lighting and heating the store during Sunday trading.\"\"\",2\n1891,\"\"\"ENROLMENT COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Enrolment costs fell dramatically by 80.9% due to the introduction of a new electronic system.\"\"\",1\n1060,\"\"\"MEANING OF GROSS PROFIT MARGIN\"\"\",\"\"\"A falling gross profit margin over time means that either the selling price at which the company sells its goods is declining, or the cost of making or buying those goods is increasing, but those increases cannot be passed on to customers. It suggests that the company's products or services are losing popularity, which raises concerns for the viability of the business. Gross profit margins may also reflect an organisation's pricing strategy.\"\"\",1\n1061,\"\"\"METHODS TO IMPROVE GROSS PROFIT MARGINS\"\"\",\"\"\"Gross profit margins may be improved by introducing new products that are popular with customers, using target costing to reduce the cost of sales, and reclassifying direct expenses as administrative.\"\"\",1\n1888,\"\"\"STAFF TRAINING COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Staff training costs increased by over $2m, a 163.9% increase, to address staff retention issues and train staff on new systems.\"\"\",1\n1607,\"\"\"STAFF COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"STAFF COSTS\"\" refer to the wages and premiums paid to employees working on Sundays and the cost of hiring additional part-time employees. Staff cost growth is calculated as $91,000/$65,000, resulting in a +40% increase. In absolute terms, average staff costs were $16,250 in 20X0, calculated from a total of $65,000 divided by four employees. The additional staff cost amounted to $26,000, which is the difference between $91,000 and $65,000, covering the expenses for two additional people.\",2\n1083,\"\"\"COMPLAINTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Complaints\"\" are expressions of dissatisfaction from customers regarding the service or product quality. The number of complaints can indicate areas needing improvement. Recently, the number of complaints has increased significantly, rising by 283% from 12 to 46. Additionally, complaints per customer visit have increased from 0.15% (12 complaints out of 8,000 visits) to 0.45% (46 complaints out of 10,225 visits).\",3\n1079,\"\"\"DELIVERY PERFORMANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Delivery performance is measured by the percentage of orders delivered within 30 minutes. It is an essential aspect of the quality of service.\"\"\",2\n1080,\"\"\"CUSTOMER RATINGS\"\"\",\"\"\"Customer ratings are scores given by customers to rate the quality of meals and service. These ratings provide insight into customer satisfaction and perceived quality.\"\"\",2\n1602,\"\"\"EVALUATING THE FINANCIAL IMPACT OF SUNDAY TRADING FOR BITS AND PIECES RETAIL STORE\"\"\",\"\"\"Bits and Pieces (B&P) is considering opening for trading on Sundays to increase revenue. The case evaluates the financial impact, including additional revenue, costs, and potential supplier discounts.\"\"\",1\n1755,\"\"\"EXTRA HOURS\"\"\",\"\"\"Extra hours refer to the additional working hours required to handle the extra orders. Here, it is calculated as 288 extra hours.\"\"\",2\n1756,\"\"\"EXTRA WAGES\"\"\",\"\"\"Extra wages refer to the additional wages paid for the extra hours worked. In this case, it amounts to $3,456.\"\"\",2\n1757,\"\"\"TOTAL FLEXED WAGES\"\"\",\"\"\"Total flexed wages = Standard wages + Extra wages. Here, it is calculated as $12,672.\"\"\",1\n1735,\"\"\"MANUFACTURING COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Manufacturing costs\"\" include variable labor production costs, other variable production costs, and fixed production costs. These costs must be covered in the long run and are a key factor in setting prices.\",1\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\n331,\"\"\"REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"ROLLING BUDGET FOR THE NEXT FOUR QUARTERS\"\"\",\"\"\"Revenue is a key component in the rolling budget for the next four quarters.\"\"\",27\n191,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"TARGET PROFIT\"\"\",\"\"\"The concept of Target Costing involves calculating the Target Profit by dividing the total required profit by the number of units to be sold.\"\"\",24\n319,\"\"\"REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"SALES PRICE\"\"\",\"\"\"Sales price contributes to Revenue as it is multiplied by the Sales units to calculate total Revenue.\"\"\",20\n326,\"\"\"REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"PERFORMANCE ASSESSMENT OF AT CO IN 20X9\"\"\",\"\"\"Revenue is a key metric in the Performance assessment of AT Co in 20X9.\"\"\",19\n322,\"\"\"REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"GROSS PROFIT MARGIN\"\"\",\"\"\"Gross profit margin is a percentage of Revenue that exceeds the cost of goods sold.\"\"\",18\n330,\"\"\"REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"NET OPERATING PROFIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Higher than expected revenue contributed to the net operating profit despite the challenging market conditions.\"\"\",18\n325,\"\"\"REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"GROSS PROFIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Gross profit is calculated by subtracting Cost of sales from Revenue.\"\"\",17\n321,\"\"\"REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"SUNDAY TRADING\"\"\",\"\"\"Sunday trading is expected to increase Revenue.\"\"\",17\n327,\"\"\"REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"MARKETING COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"The increase in marketing costs helped attract new students, contributing to higher revenue.\"\"\",15\n320,\"\"\"REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"TARGET REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"Target revenue is the projected total Revenue that a company aims to achieve.\"\"\",15\n328,\"\"\"REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"INTERACTIVE WEBSITE\"\"\",\"\"\"The introduction of the interactive website contributed to higher student numbers and revenue.\"\"\",14\n324,\"\"\"REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"MANAGER'S BONUS\"\"\",\"\"\"Manager's bonus is based on the extra Revenue generated by Sunday trading.\"\"\",14\n323,\"\"\"REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"SUPPLIER DISCOUNT\"\"\",\"\"\"Supplier discount is related to Revenue as it provides a reduction in purchase price when certain conditions are met.\"\"\",14\n329,\"\"\"REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"STUDENT HELPLINE\"\"\",\"\"\"The introduction of the student helpline contributed to higher student numbers and revenue.\"\"\",14\n1442,\"\"\"NON-FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE INDICATORS\"\"\",\"\"\"PERFORMANCE ASSESSMENT OF AT CO IN 20X9\"\"\",\"\"\"Non-financial performance indicators are used in the Performance assessment of AT Co in 20X9 to provide a comprehensive view of the company's performance.\"\"\",12\n1705,\"\"\"COST OF SALES\"\"\",\"\"\"PERFORMANCE ASSESSMENT OF AT CO IN 20X9\"\"\",\"\"\"Cost of sales is a key metric in the Performance assessment of AT Co in 20X9.\"\"\",11\n1709,\"\"\"NET OPERATING PROFIT\"\"\",\"\"\"PERFORMANCE ASSESSMENT OF AT CO IN 20X9\"\"\",\"\"\"Net operating profit is a key metric in the Performance assessment of AT Co in 20X9.\"\"\",11\n1051,\"\"\"GROSS PROFIT MARGIN\"\"\",\"\"\"COST OF SALES\"\"\",\"\"\"The reduction in cost of sales contributed to the increase in gross profit margin.\"\"\",10\n342,\"\"\"GROSS PROFIT\"\"\",\"\"\"PERFORMANCE ASSESSMENT OF AT CO IN 20X9\"\"\",\"\"\"Gross profit is a key metric in the Performance assessment of AT Co in 20X9.\"\"\",10\n341,\"\"\"GROSS PROFIT\"\"\",\"\"\"NET OPERATING PROFIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Net operating profit is derived from Gross profit after deducting Indirect expenses.\"\"\",9\n1708,\"\"\"INDIRECT EXPENSES\"\"\",\"\"\"PERFORMANCE ASSESSMENT OF AT CO IN 20X9\"\"\",\"\"\"Indirect expenses are a